					<description><![CDATA[<p>Series C Financing Strengthens Clinical and Regulatory Pathway CereVasc has raised $85 million in Series C financing. Piper Sandler Merchant Banking led the funding round. The company, based in Massachusetts,</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/cerevasc-raises-85m-series-c-brain-treatment/" data-wpel-link="internal">CereVasc Raises $85M Series C to Advance Minimally Invasive Brain Treatment Platform</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<h2><b>Series C Financing Strengthens Clinical and Regulatory Pathway</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">CereVasc has raised $85 million in Series C financing. Piper Sandler Merchant Banking led the funding round. The company, based in Massachusetts, just hit a key clinical milestone with this investment. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The new funds will help keep the eShunt System moving forward and get things ready for commercial launch. Other investors include Johnson &amp; Johnson Innovation, Medtronic, Bain Capital Life Sciences, and Perceptive Xontogeny Venture Funds—a strong mix of players from healthcare and life sciences.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">With this backing, the company plans to ramp up operations and grow its team. Clinical and regulatory work will stay front and center. The new funding also boosts corporate governance, with fresh faces joining the board to help steer the next phase of growth.</span></p>
<h2><b>eShunt System Targets Neurological Disease Treatment</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">CereVasc develops minimally invasive treatments for </span><a href="https://my.clevelandclinic.org/health/diseases/neurological-disorders" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">neurological conditions</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">. Its lead product is the eShunt System. It targets patients with normal pressure hydrocephalus. The system delivers cerebrospinal fluid drainage through a minimally invasive approach. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">It avoids traditional brain surgery. This reduces procedural risk and recovery time. The treatment is designed for communicating hydrocephalus. This condition impacts cerebrospinal fluid flow in the brain. Current treatment relies on invasive shunt surgery.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The STRIDE pivotal trial is currently underway. It is a multi-centre and randomised clinical study. It compares eShunt against ventriculo-peritoneal shunts. Trial results will support a future FDA submission. The company is targeting Premarket Approval. This step is required for commercialisation. The system includes an implantable shunt device. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">It is delivered through an endovascular approach. The design aims to improve precision and safety. Clinical development remains the top priority. The company is advancing through regulated trial stages. Each phase supports eventual market approval.</span></p>
<h2><b>Strategic Investors Back Neuroscience Innovation</b></h2>
<div id="attachment_202408" style="width: 1322px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-202408" class="size-full wp-image-202408" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/CereVasc-2.png" alt="Illustration of neuroscience innovation supported by institutional investors, showing advanced brain medical technology, neurovascular systems, and medtech commercialization progress." width="1312" height="736" /><p id="caption-attachment-202408" class="wp-caption-text">Strategic institutional investors are accelerating neuroscience innovation, supporting minimally invasive neurological treatments, strengthened governance structures, and the advancement of medical device technologies addressing critical unmet clinical needs. Source: Created by Ventureburn.</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The financing attracted major healthcare investors. Johnson &amp; Johnson Innovation participated through its venture arm. Medtronic also joined the round. Piper Sandler Merchant Banking led the investment. Bain Capital Life Sciences and Perceptive Xontogeny also participated. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The group reflects strong institutional backing.The global medical device market continues to expand. Demand is rising for minimally invasive treatments. Neurological care remains a key growth area. CereVasc also strengthened its board structure.  Kevin Conroy joins as lead independent director. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Christopher Geyen becomes audit committee chair. Tom Schnettler joins the board representing Piper Sandler. These additions bring financial and operational expertise. Governance is being aligned with commercial readiness. The company emphasises patient impact as a core mission. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Leadership highlights unmet medical needs. Existing treatments remain limited in effectiveness and accessibility. The investment reflects confidence in clinical innovation. Strategic partners support both development and future commercialisation. This strengthens long-term positioning.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/airspeed-raises-20m-series-a-revenue-execution/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">Airspeed Raises $20M Series A to Scale Agent-Native Revenue Execution Platform</span></a></p>
<h2><b>Expansion, Commercial Readiness and Market Opportunity</b></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">CereVasc will use funding to scale operations. The company’s getting ready to launch commercially soon, and that means it’s growing fast. Clinical trials are still front and center — STRIDE is built to deliver regulatory-grade data, and that’ll help with FDA approval talks. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The eShunt System is a whole new way to treat patients. It’s supposed to cut down on invasive neurosurgery, which could really change how doctors manage hydrocephalus. They’re part of Massachusetts biotech, a major hub offering strong access to medical research and clinical expertise.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Leadership’s pushing hard toward being ready for market. Regulatory submission is a big hurdle, and manufacturing is set to ramp up. Dan Levangie, CEO of CereVasc, called the latest funding a huge milestone. For him, it’s all about improving patient outcomes and being ready for commercial launch.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Neurological devices are a growing market — people want safer, less invasive options, and companies are pouring money into new ideas. CereVasc slots right into that trend, focusing on making procedures simpler and more effective. The next phase will show whether they can really break into the commercial market.</span></p>
