					<description><![CDATA[<p>FirstClub, a curated online grocery startup, announced a $55 million Series B funding. The round was led by Peak XV Partners and led by a global investment firm, Sofina. The</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/firstclub-raises-55m-in-series-b-led-by-peak-xv-sofina/" data-wpel-link="internal">FirstClub Raises $55M in Series B Led by Peak XV, Sofina</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="https://www.firstclub.site/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">FirstClub</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">, a curated online grocery startup, announced a $55 million Series B </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/merantix-capital-launches-e103m-fund-for-european-ai/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">funding</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">. The round was led by Peak XV Partners and led by a global investment firm, Sofina. The startup&#8217;s post-money valuation is now at $255 million, which is well over 2X its valuation at the time of the fundraise about 10 months ago.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Existing institutional investors such as Accel, RTP Global, and Paramark Ventures were also very active during this fundraising phase. This fresh influx of capital brings FirstClub’s total funds raised to date to $86 million. The round reflects a growing appetite among venture capitalists for e-commerce models that favour unit economics and quality assurance over low-margin speed races.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">The Antithesis of Quick Commerce</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Founded in September 2024 by former Flipkart executive and Cleartrip CEO Ayyappan R., FirstClub was engineered to push back against the standard industry playbook. Although leading local players Blinkit, Zepto and Swiggy Instamart focus exclusively on sub-ten-minute delivery times, attracting customers through huge discounts and offering lakhs of different products, FirstClub runs on a totally different axis.</span></p>
<div id="attachment_202397" style="width: 1034px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-202397" class="size-large wp-image-202397" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/06/grocery-store-1024x768.jpg" alt="grocery store" width="1024" height="768" /><p id="caption-attachment-202397" class="wp-caption-text">Source: Unsplash</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The firm builds itself on consumer trust, rigorous ingredient bans, and lab-assayed freshness. FirstClub offers the most rigorous control of its inventory, offering a smaller (about 4000 SKUs), extremely efficient, checked inventory targeted essentially at health-oriented consumers and families.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Every product is thoroughly checked before they land on the digital shelves. For instance, the company deploys chemist testing devices like Brix for measuring the sweetness level in fruits, followed by lab tests for all daily fresh staples such as milk, flour, paneer, and lentils. Also, FirstClub does not allow over 200 standard additives, such as growth hormones, antibiotics, preservatives, etc.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/merantix-capital-launches-e103m-fund-for-european-ai/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">Merantix Capital Launches €103M Fund for European AI</span></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">A Premium on Unit Economics</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The startup’s specialised focus has yielded notable performance figures in a sector often plagued by high cash-burn rates. FirstClub reports an average basket size of roughly 1,200 Indian Rupees ($14.40 USD). This average order value tracks at nearly two and a half times the prevailing quick commerce industry standard, heavily driven by consumers purchasing full-basket grocery arrays rather than individual immediate needs.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Rather than pricing its inventory at a steep premium, the platform attributes the higher transaction values to the depth of individual orders. Customers routinely clear ten or eleven items per checkout. By pairing these larger basket sizes with a deliberate order-batching strategy and a smaller number of stock-keeping units, FirstClub claims to be intentionally baking strong unit economics directly into its growth phase, rather than trying to fix margins after achieving scale.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Roadmap for Strategic Scale</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">FirstClub has handled its physical expansion with a conservative footprint relative to standard multi-city operators. The startup currently manages 24 specialised fulfilment hubs, which it designates as clubhouses. Twenty-one of these fulfilment centres are located within its home base of Bengaluru, covering roughly 85% of high-density zip codes. </span>The company recently opened the remaining three hubs to seed a presence in Hyderabad.</p>
<p>The company will channel the newly acquired $55 million toward warehouse infrastructure, fulfilment technology, and expanding clubhouses to 35 centres by year-end. Beyond structural expansion, FirstClub plans a significant category push into non-grocery sectors. Over the next quarter, the application will introduce dedicated verticals for beauty and personal care, domestic essentials, kitchenware, and pet care supplies.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/firstclub-raises-55m-in-series-b-led-by-peak-xv-sofina/" data-wpel-link="internal">FirstClub Raises $55M in Series B Led by Peak XV, Sofina</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
			</item>
